args: Thanks for taking us to Lucretia's recital,\nVixel.
It's the least I could do, considering the\nlarge volume of tickets I received.
I think it was her subtle way of telling me\nto bring all of you along.
Just so. Thank you for coming, everyone.
I worked it out so you'll be able to watch\nrehearsals as well as the performance,\nso I hope you enjoy.
Typical of Lucretia to put on such a moving\nperformance even in rehearsal.
Were ya totally overwhelmed by Lucretia's\nsingin' there, kid?
Oh, it was undoubtedly amazing—\nand yet, I can't help but wonder if\nLucretia is all right.
Something about her voice felt...\nI don't know. Different, somehow.
It came from the back! C'mon!
Apparently she had been suffering in\nsilence from a rather nasty bug.
But she didn't look sick at all during\nthe rehearsal.
She was planning to tough it out until the\nend of the actual recital.
I have her resting in the dressing room,\nbut I'm not certain she'll be able to sing\nin her current condition.
So what's that mean for the recital?
Will we be forced to cancel?
Don't be a fool! Look at how many\nguests we have here today!
There will be a riot if we cancel now!
Then what should we do? Wait and hope\nher condition improves?
I will sing in her place!
This is no time for games, child!
And I'm not playing one. But unless you\nhappen to have a better idea...
Our guests have come to hear LUCRETIA.\nNot you.
Then I will simply be the opening act,\nwhich should give Lucretia time to recover.
And what, exactly, do you plan to sing?
What songs does the orchestra know?
I have a list right here...
Hmm... All the classical standards...\nAh. What about this one?
Have you gone mad, child?!\nThat piece is exceptionally difficult!
And it's rather too dark when contrasted\nagainst Lucretia's upcoming program.
In that case, how about I sing the melody\nan octave higher to brighten it up?
I suppose that might add a bit more levity\nto the proceedings.
The audience likely won't expect a\nclassical opening like this; I imagine\nthe surprise will be rather delightful.

I know how skilled the orchestra is based
on their rehearsal, so I imagine this song
is one they will be able to handle despite
its difficulty, yes?
My singing is only a small part, after all.\nThe music itself will be the key.
And skillful playing will make them all the\nmore excited to hear Lucretia.
Which is really the point of an opening act,\ndon't you think?
That's a shockingly sound analysis\nconsidering he's only heard us\nrehearse this one time.
Maybe so—but being an opening act for\nsomeone like Lucretia is a lot of pressure.\nAre we sure this child can pull it off?
Now YOU have gone mad, Vixel!
I have heard him sing time and again.\nHe can do it, I assure you.
At any rate, I believe his plan is preferable\nto canceling the performance outright.\nOr am I mistaken?
Hmm... If someone as skilled as you is\nadvocating for him, perhaps we need to\nreconsider our position.
Very well—we'll start going over the score.\nCome, child. We've much work to do.
You sure you're good with this, Elias?!
You say that, and yet your hands are\nshaking like leaves.
I know your singing can win this audience\nover, Elias. I believe in you.
(I'm so glad Lucretia's able to sing again.)
(And it's just as gorgeous as I knew it\nwould be! Oh, if only I could sing like\nher someday...)
Thank you so much for coming to our show\ntonight, ladies and gentlemen.
Phew! She got through it without\nany trouble.
You were a big part of tonight's success,\nElias. Your singing was exceptional.
It is astounding that your number came\ntogether in so short a time.
That's some real dynamite work there, kid.\nThe audience ate it up!
Still...I think it's because all of you were\nhere that I was able to pull off something\nso audacious.
Heh. You're just saying whatever pops into\nyour head today. Must be leftover courage\nfrom your big performance.
Heh, I suppose I am.\n...Ah, Lucretia.
Thank you so much for what you did today,\nElias. You saved the performance.
I heard you from backstage—your work\nwas incredibly moving.
I see now that your singing has changed.\nIt is replete with passion, and even gave\nme strength as I waited to come on.
Might you be willing to accompany me on\nmy next tour?
The orchestra has actually been asking\nme if you're going to come—they seem\nto have grown rather fond of you.
They want ME to come on YOUR tour?!
Yes—as do I. So what is your answer?
Nice job, kid! This is exactly what ya been\nwaitin' for, yeah?
I can think of no reason why you might\ndecline this offer.
I got better at singing because I came to\nthe Halidom.
Obviously I can study and improve by\nworking with Lucretia...
But I feel like what I'm learning at the\nHalidom is ALSO helpful.
In that case, you can rejoin us once the\ntour is over.
After all, shouldn't you be studying both\nsinging AND other things?
Would that really be all right?
Of course! Honestly, I'd like to hear you\nsing again, so it's not like this is a\ncompletely selfless offer.
Well then? Does that assuage any\nhesitation you may have felt?
Just you watch! I'm gonna grow even more\nand then come back to the Halidom!
Best of luck on the tour, Elias.
I'll see you all again soon!
